## 10. Risks & Mitigations

| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |
|------|--------|------------|
| Simli latency spikes | User experience degrades | Implement idle avatar animation, pre-buffer first question |
| LLM hallucinates / gives advice | Violates core requirement | Strict system prompt + output validation + fallback responses |
| User becomes distressed | Safety concern | Sentiment monitoring + emergency script + session recording |
| Deepgram misses words | Wrong LLM decisions | Use interim + final transcripts, confidence threshold |
| WebRTC connectivity issues | Session drops | Auto-reconnect logic, session state persistence |

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **TTS Service Choice**: Simli does NOT provide TTS. We need a separate service:
> - **ElevenLabs** — Best voice quality (~$0.30/1000 chars), slightly higher latency
> - **Cartesia** — Lower latency (~200ms), good quality, better for real-time
> 
> **Which do you prefer?** For MVP with low-latency focus, I recommend **Cartesia**.

> [!IMPORTANT]  
> **Pipecat vs Custom Pipeline**: I strongly recommend using **Pipecat** as the real-time pipeline framework (instead of writing custom WebSocket/WebRTC code from scratch). It handles VAD, streaming, and Simli integration out of the box. Your FastAPI backend would still exist for REST APIs, database, and business logic — but the real-time audio/video flow goes through Pipecat. **Are you comfortable with adding Pipecat to the stack?**

> [!WARNING]
> **Hosting Consideration**: Pipecat requires a server that can maintain WebRTC connections (not serverless). You'll need a persistent server (VM, container) for the Pipecat pipeline. This affects deployment architecture.
